 writing. The book combines studies of familiar and lesser known texts, from the poems and plays of Shakespeare to jests and printed commonplace books. Its ten studies make important, original contributions to research on the genres of early modern literature, focusing on the involvement of literary forms in the scribal and print cultures of compilation, continuation, translation, and correspondence, as well as in matters of political republicanism and popular piety, among others. Taken together, the collection’s essays exemplify how an attention to form and matter can historicise writing without abandoning a literary focus.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEnglish literaturexHistory and criticismxTheory, etcxEarly modern, 1500-1700. 0aEnglish literatureyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 4aShakespeare 2018. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Renaissance.2bisacsh  aEnglish renaissance literature.  abook history.  aearly modern literature.  ahistorical formalism.  aliterary form.  amaterial texts.1 aBailey, Amanda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeutermann, Allison K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeutermann, Allison, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJames, Heather, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKastan, David Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKisery, Andras, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKiséry, András, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnight, Jeffrey Todd, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLake, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPollard, Tanya, econtributor.4ct